From Vesselin Bontchev Subject Re Clipper considered harmful brad Brad Yearwood writes Criminals who very badly want inscrutable tactical communications specificall the terrorists and drug dealers who proponents of key escrow cite as threats will be highly motivated to steal the cipher phone of a legitimate user and to kill this person or hold them hostage so discovery of compromise of the device will be Why doing it in such a rough manner It is much more professional to steal the chip from the phone and even to replace it with a pin compatible do nothing chip that does not encrypt at Chances are that the victim will not notice anything especially if it is done Once a suitable collection of devices is stolen criminals can communicate with impunity assuming the cipher system carries no trapdoors apart from key escrow until and unless the compromise is discovered by some other No because the Feds will still be able to decrypt the True they'll blame the wrong guys but nevertheless one cannot say something like The drugs arrive tommorrow on the ship 'Terminus' when the Feds are listening even if they cannot identify who the speaker No the criminals will just use some secure The new proposal does not stop criminals it ensures that the government will be able to wiretap the average citizen and stops the casual To me it also clearly looks as a step towards outlawing any other strong encryption Regards Vesselin Vesselin Vladimirov Bontchev Virus Test Center University of Hamburg Fax Fachbereich Informatik AGN PGP public key available on Vogt Koelln Strasse C e mail D Hamburg Germany